        "text": "θέλεις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because he had already been delivered over to the higher Roman authority, and accordingly as a Roman citizen could not be compelled again to renounce the Roman tribunal.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If Festus had previously (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") without ceremony refused the request of the Jews, which was at variance with the course of Roman law, he now shows, on the other hand, after they had conformed to the ordinary mode of procedure, that he was quite willing to please them. Certainly he could not doubt beforehand that his ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θέλεις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would be answered in the negative by Paul; yet by his question he made the Jews sensible at least that the frustration of their wish did not proceed from any indisposition on his part.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "χάριν καταθέσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τοῖς Ἰ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., best placed emphatically before ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "χάριν κατ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". (W.H[391]), so as to show that it was the compliance of Festus to the Jews which caused the turn which things took (Weiss).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θέλεις εἰς Ἱ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: “injustum videbatur condemnare, incommodum absolvere,” Blass.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκεῖ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": he makes himself the same proposal to the prisoner which had previously been suggested by the accusers, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπʼ ἐμοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": “me præsente,” for the Sanhedrists would be the judges; otherwise, where would be the favour to the Jews? Felix may have added the words ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "speciose",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so as to reassure Paul and to obtain his acquiescence to the proposal; in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " omitted, but evidently from their close connection with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "περὶ τούτ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κρίν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". they indicate that Festus would play some judicial part in the matter; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But Paul’s answer plainly shows that he thought from the words of Felix that a Jewish and not a Roman tribunal awaited him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπʼ ἐμοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would therefore seem to mean that the Sanhedrim would judge, whilst Festus would ratify their judgment or not as seemed good to him, as Pilate had acted in the case of Christ. On the other hand it is possible that Festus may have been quite sincere in his proposal: his words at least showed that in his judgment there was no case against Paul of a political nature, and he may have thought that religious questions could be best decided before the Sanhedrim in Jerusalem, whilst he could guarantee a safe-conduct for Paul as a Roman citizen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[391] Westcott and Hort’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The New Testament in Greek:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Critical Text and Notes.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But Festus, willing to do the Jews a pleasure",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Better (with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") “desiring to gain favour with the Jews.” Cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Though he had not consented to their request when he was in Jerusalem, he now went some way towards doing so by his question to Paul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wilt thou … before me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] What Festus proposed was equivalent to acquitting the Apostle of any charge which would come under Roman law. He is therefore appealed to on the other accusations. The offences against the law of the Jews and against the Temple must be heard before the Sanhedrin. Would Paul accept an acquittal on one count and submit to a trial before his own people on the rest? And Festus would be present to see that right was done.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Θέλεις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wilt thou?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Festus could have given the decree without asking Paul; but conscience kept him back, and the matter was divinely so ordered, that Paul should be given cause for making an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "appeal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπʼ ἐμοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "before me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") This Festus adds plausibly. Paul answers presently, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπὶ τοῦ βήματος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "before the tribunal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- Desiring to gain",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " favor ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "with the Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "willing to do the Jews a pleasure",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To gain favor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. (see above, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note). It was not unnatural that Festus, ignorant as he still was of Jewish malice and bigotry and violence, in the case of Paul, and anxious to conciliate a people so difficult to govern as the Jews had showed themselves to be, should make the proposal. In doing so he still insisted that the trial should be before him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Before me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐπ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐμοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Acts 26:2; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐπὶ σοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"before thee,\" viz. King Agrippa in the last case, and Felix in the former. The expression is somewhat ambiguous, and may merely mean that Festus would be present in the court to ensure fair play, while the Sanhedrim judged Paul according to their Law, and so Paul seems, by his answer, to have understood it. Acts 25:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Do a pleasure",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "See on Acts 24:27. Rev., better, to gain favor.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 24:27",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Rev., better, to gain favor.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Before me ( ἐπ' ἐμοῦ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Not with him as judge, but by the Sanhedrim in his presence. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
